Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

The patch is broken since we don't depend on retrying library in Icehouse. I don't think we're able to introduce the backport as-is since retrying is not even included in global requirements repo for Icehouse release. This means we'll introduce a completely new dependency in the middle of release support cycle, and we cannot afford it.

Can we rework the patch to avoid depending on the module?

Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

The core functionality of the retrying library [0] is simple, and could be inlined. A cleaner and probably safer option would be to use the decorator directly from nova [1], which is what was originally proposed when the retrying decorator was added. [2]

[0] https://github.com/rholder/retrying/blob/master/retrying.py#L212-236
[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py#L176-191
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/106764/

Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Revisiting after the discussion.

This is not 1:1 cherry pick from the one that landed to master nor stable/Juno as the retrying module is not available in the stable/icehouse.

Thus I think this needs to be verified before bringing in to stable icehouse.

Ankit: Please send e-mail to openstack-dev mailing list with [Glance][Stable] flags in subject explaining what you had to bring in so stable-maint-core can review this before merging.

Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Under the new stable policy, Icehouse is current in phase II support, so only critical bugs and security fixes are considered for backport. This does not seem to pass the "critical" bar to me, it seems more like a bugfix for a corner case -- unless I'm mistaken users can still retry the image deletion manually if they get a 500 error)

It's also a non-trivial patch (not a straight backport from something that has been battle-tested in master) so I don't think we should give this an "obviously safe" exception.

Patch Set 5:

Hi Thierry,

If db deadlock occurs in glance registry before updating the deleted flag of image to True, in this case glance-api returns 500 error to user and the image gets status=deleted and deleted=False.

User can see these images using "glance image-list".
User can also see image details using "glance image-show <image_id>" where he can find status as deleted and deleted=False, but no one can delete this image any more.

Now if either user or admin retries to delete this image then,

1. In case of v1 api it returns 404 (Not Found) error.
2. In case of v2 api it returns 500 (HTTPInternalServerError).

IMO, As user can see these images in the list but not able to delete them anymore this is a critical issue.

Please let me know your opinion on this.

Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

Downgrading my vote to +0 since the persistence of the issue makes it more "critical" than I thought.
